DIGEST
The digest printed below was prepared by House Legislative Services. It constitutes no part
of the legislative instrument. The keyword, one-liner, abstract, and digest do not constitute
part of the law or proof or indicia of legislative intent. [R.S. 1:13(B) and 24:177(E)]
HB 4 Original 2025 First Extraordinary Session Bayham
Abstract: Provides for the 2026 fall primary election to serve as a primary election for
party primary offices and for the 2026 fall general election to serve as a general
election for party primary offices.
Present law effective January 1, 2026, provides that there shall be a fall primary election
held on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November for officers elected at the same
time as members of congress in that year. Proposed law retains present law.
Present law provides that the fall primary election date shall also serve as the general
election date for a party primary office to be elected in a congressional election year and
provides that the candidate who receives the most votes cast for a party primary office in the
general election is elected.
Proposed law instead provides that the 2026 fall primary election shall serve as a primary
election date for a party primary office to be elected in 2026 and provides that a party
primary office candidate who receives a majority of the votes cast for the office in the
primary election is elected.
Present law effective January 1, 2026, provides that there shall be a fall general election held
on the sixth Saturday after the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November of a
congressional election year and does not include party primary offices in the fall general
election.
Proposed law provides that the 2026 fall general election shall also serve as a general
election date for a party primary office to be elected in 2026 and provides that a party
primary office candidate who receives the most votes cast for the office in the general
election is elected.
Effective upon signature of governor or lapse of time for gubernatorial action.
(Adds R.S. 18:419)
